data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime — with no opt-in to restore the old behavior.**

In EF Core 10 you could opt in to sync-over-async, but EF Core 11 **fully removed** that escape hatch. Every synchronous I/O API (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) now **always throws** against the Cosmos DB provider.

### What to fix

Convert every method to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This means callers must propagate `async/await` up the call chain as well. There is no workaround — the Cosmos DB SDK is async-only and EF Core 11 no longer bridges the gap.
